WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.200
Welcome to Motley Crews Collaborating with Quarto.

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:10.480
My name is Will Schuth.

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:17.240
I'm going to be presenting with my colleagues Susan McMillan and Mike Zent.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:19.959
This is our Motley Crew.

00:00:19.959 --> 00:00:24.160
Pictured on the right is the director of our office and a drummer, Mike Fleger, who's

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.559
not able to join us today.

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:32.520
We are a team of analysts for the Liberal Arts College at the University of Wisconsin-Madison.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:38.279
We analyze student outcomes for administration and faculty.

00:00:38.279 --> 00:00:46.360
And an important thing to know about us is that none of us are data scientists or developers.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:49.799
We work in a collaborative environment where our different types of analyses and professional

00:00:49.799 --> 00:00:52.959
backgrounds often contribute to a single analytic product.

00:00:52.959 --> 00:01:04.720
Our backgrounds are, I'm a historian, Susan's a political scientist, and Mike is a philosopher.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:10.040
I conduct mainly narrative analyses of curriculum and university academic policy.

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:16.320
I'm also our primary editor, and I've been writing in Markdown for years.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:21.199
As we began to work together and increase our collaboration, we quickly realized that

00:01:21.199 --> 00:01:24.559
we had a significant problem.

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:29.040
And our problem was that we had fragmented workflows.

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:33.919
So every time that we attempted a collaborative analysis, we were dealing with an assemblage

00:01:33.919 --> 00:01:42.000
of data that was obtained using query tools like Hyperion and Toad Data Point and SQL

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.879
Developer that we then analyzed using Excel, or R as the situation called for.

00:01:47.879 --> 00:01:49.180
We plotted it.

00:01:49.180 --> 00:01:55.059
We merged it with narrative analyses that were written and drawn from flat files that

00:01:55.059 --> 00:02:02.660
were stored in Obsidian or other PKMs, and then that we tailored together in Word, published

00:02:02.660 --> 00:02:07.139
as a PDF because, my goodness, do people like their PDFs?

00:02:07.139 --> 00:02:12.899
And then we distributed to our audiences via email.

00:02:12.899 --> 00:02:17.839
This workflow, we quickly realized, was unsustainable.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:20.240
We needed to find a better way for us to work together.

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:25.520
Keep in mind also, this is happening after our university has gone remote during COVID,

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:27.000
and so we're each working remotely.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.320
We don't have an opportunity to meet together to do these things.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:32.360
We have to unite our work in some way.

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:38.039
So what we're going to talk to you is how we abandoned this and what we learned as we

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:40.080
came to a new way of working together.

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:45.119
I'm going to share with you why the form of the work matters.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:50.360
Susan's going to speak about how our new way of working together reduced barriers for the

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:54.399
non-technical collaborators that we have.

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:58.839
And Mike's going to share with you how this new way has enhanced the accuracy of the work

00:02:58.839 --> 00:03:00.639
that we do.

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:04.360
So why does form matter?

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:10.759
I'm going to use some visual metaphors here that are from the local area.

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:17.240
Design hurdles at the end of a long analytic project are mentally exhausting, and they

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:19.520
can be very frustrating.

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:26.479
As I shared, we were assembling draft and final analytic products by merging analyses

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:31.440
that were drawn from different areas into a Word document.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:36.520
And we quickly realized that, like the James R. Thompson Center, which you see here, pictured

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.960
you could visit a short walk down West Randolph from where we are.

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:44.720
This became a maintenance nightmare for us.

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:50.899
Every single time that we were asked to add a plot, when we realized that we needed to

00:03:50.899 --> 00:03:56.240
edit a caption, or when we thought, you know what, this section of this analysis really

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:02.199
belongs somewhere else because it amplifies a message that we need our audiences to get.

00:04:02.199 --> 00:04:03.199
It was a maintenance nightmare.

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:07.559
We revisited it every single time that we had one of those.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:12.279
You may be familiar with the adage, form follows function.

00:04:12.279 --> 00:04:17.980
This comes from a principle of design that was advanced by Louis Sullivan, who's a prominent

00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:20.480
Chicago school architect.

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:28.000
Sullivan went so far as to say that form following function was a law of human design.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.239
You can see his ethos in many buildings that he designed around Chicago.

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:38.920
This is the auditorium building, which you can visit in a short walk down Michigan Avenue.

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:43.200
This photo was taken in 1890, about a year after the building was completed.

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:48.559
And with respect to Sullivan, who was certainly at the forefront of his field when the 19th

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:52.679
century turned to the 20th century, we realized that for folks who do the kind of work that

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:57.779
we and many of you do, this simply doesn't go far enough.

00:04:57.779 --> 00:05:04.660
So what we'd suggest instead is that the form of the work is its function.

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:10.279
Like the John Hancock Center, the structure of the analysis that we create in our new

00:05:10.279 --> 00:05:13.980
way of working together is visible in the final analytic product.

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:18.299
It's visible to us on the back end when we're looking at the source, when we can see how

00:05:18.299 --> 00:05:23.260
we structured the query, when we can see the R code that we use to analyze the data that

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:27.820
we obtain from our query, when we can see the comments that'll explain to us seven

00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:32.260
months down the line when we've forgotten why we queried things the way that we did,

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:35.579
what we were trying to do, and the other things that we tried.

00:05:35.579 --> 00:05:39.179
None of that's visible to our audiences, but it's there.

00:05:39.179 --> 00:05:43.380
And because we can more easily accommodate other requests that our audiences have, that

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:46.980
structure is something that we can fall back on to do our work better.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:51.500
So the form of our final analysis facilitates its function now.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:55.779
And the function of producing our analysis fashions its final form.

00:05:55.779 --> 00:05:58.779
How did we get there?

00:05:58.779 --> 00:06:01.579
We realized we had to embrace Conway's Law.

00:06:01.579 --> 00:06:09.500
Melvin Conway is a computer scientist, and he suggested that any organization that attempts

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:16.220
to design a product or a system is going to inevitably in some way replicate that organization's

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:19.540
structure within that product.

00:06:19.579 --> 00:06:24.420
The example is, if you have a four-person group working on something and you need to

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:28.700
build a bypass, you're going to have a four-component bypass.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:30.640
That's the basic concept.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:34.760
And what we realized is that we have disparate backgrounds that draw on different analytic

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:38.980
styles, and we needed to find a way to bring those together.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:45.260
We needed to unify the production environment for our analyses, and we needed to unify our

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:47.220
workflow.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:49.380
And so that's what we did.

00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:55.140
We adopted a unified workflow that allows us to leverage RStudio and Quarto as the single

00:06:55.140 --> 00:07:00.540
place where we now query, process, analyze, and visualize data for our audiences, and

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:04.619
where we write our narrative analyses and our executive summaries that we can share

00:07:04.619 --> 00:07:08.540
with those audiences to help them make sense of the data that we've given them.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:13.339
Because we're working oftentimes remotely and in different places from each other, and

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:16.820
we're working on different components of the analysis, it's really important that we have

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:17.980
version control.

00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:22.260
You may use GitHub for version control, we use GitLab for our version control, so that

00:07:22.260 --> 00:07:29.019
when I'm working on doing some copy editing in a nearly final draft, and Mike and Susan

00:07:29.019 --> 00:07:32.540
are tweaking plots or doing some other things, maybe accommodating a last-minute request

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:38.299
from a stakeholder, we're not getting in each other's way, and we're not having to recompile

00:07:38.299 --> 00:07:42.660
a PDF document to incorporate those changes.

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:46.940
And once we've reached the point where our document is finished and we feel like the

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:52.299
analysis is ready to share with our audiences, we can publish it online using the pages feature

00:07:52.299 --> 00:07:57.179
of GitLab, and our audiences can view the document there, and if we have other things

00:07:57.179 --> 00:08:00.140
that need to be updated, it can be updated.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:05.220
Now Susan's going to share with you how this new workflow has reduced technical barriers

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:07.100
for our collaborators.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:09.380
Thanks, Will.

00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:16.540
Susan McMillan, I am the social scientist in our group, and despite many years of writing

00:08:16.540 --> 00:08:24.380
scripted code for multiple software packages, I embody the non-technical user.

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:29.540
Computers still are mysterious to me, I don't know any Markdown, I didn't even, I never

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:34.500
heard of Markdown actually, I didn't know what a CSS file was.

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:40.400
I worked in a company before I came to this job where we did that painful copy-paste process

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:46.260
for every document we produced, analytic document, and it could be a really big document.

00:08:46.979 --> 00:08:53.219
But I produced a table, or a graph, or text, and I gave it to the document production team,

00:08:53.219 --> 00:08:57.940
and the document production team put all the disparate pieces together, and then they shipped

00:08:57.940 --> 00:09:00.140
it out to the client.

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:05.739
We are the document production team now, we're also the analysis team, we're everything,

00:09:05.739 --> 00:09:07.460
so this was not tenable.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:12.859
So when I got here, Mike was kind of our studio missionary, and he said, no, we're going to

00:09:12.859 --> 00:09:16.020
do this in R Markdown, I was like, okay.

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:20.299
So I started learning R Markdown, which was probably a little bit painful for Mike, because

00:09:20.299 --> 00:09:24.539
we were still producing PDF files, and so I also had to learn a little bit of LaTeX,

00:09:24.539 --> 00:09:28.619
which was completely mysterious, but we were trying.

00:09:28.619 --> 00:09:34.380
And then, our studio conference last year, we were introduced to Corto, and we're like,

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:36.260
well, there it is.

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:44.580
So we went home and very rapidly turned our process into one that begins and ends with

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:49.200
R Studio and Corto, and this is what happened.

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:54.979
We are able to use the visual editor, so the point of this slide is only in the top corner,

00:09:54.979 --> 00:10:01.140
with the switch, the toggle between visual and source code, and the table is there, but

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:07.219
the point here is that it's familiar enough to people who use Word, or some other word

00:10:07.219 --> 00:10:11.619
processor, but we'll just go with Word, that they can do things in this file.

00:10:11.619 --> 00:10:17.580
So our supervisor, who's our expert at both policy and curriculum, needs to be able to

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:22.619
write and edit in our documents, and he's able to do that here.

00:10:22.619 --> 00:10:25.619
He's able to see, oh, if I want a bold text, I can do it.

00:10:25.619 --> 00:10:28.179
If I want italicized text, I can do it.

00:10:28.179 --> 00:10:31.059
If I want to add a bullet list, I can do that.

00:10:31.979 --> 00:10:35.820
So he doesn't want to learn R or R Markdown, and frankly, he's a little bit afraid of seeing

00:10:35.820 --> 00:10:36.820
the code.

00:10:36.820 --> 00:10:39.059
Like, I might put the table in like this.

00:10:39.059 --> 00:10:40.539
He doesn't want to see that, right?

00:10:40.539 --> 00:10:42.460
He wants to see just this.

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:46.260
And it works for both of us, same file.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:55.059
And as Will said, we can now publish our results to webpages.

00:10:55.059 --> 00:10:59.500
Mind you, the only point of this slide is that I published it as a webpage.

00:10:59.619 --> 00:11:01.859
I don't know HTML.

00:11:01.859 --> 00:11:04.780
I don't know anything about publications.

00:11:04.780 --> 00:11:11.179
I just pushed it to GitLab, and it was magically there.

00:11:11.179 --> 00:11:14.780
So that's the whole point of this slide, that I was able to do it.

00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:19.179
And so Corto reduced massively the technical barriers.

00:11:19.179 --> 00:11:22.900
It's not a chance I could have published a website on my own.

00:11:22.900 --> 00:11:27.200
Well, it would have taken a lot, but I mean, yeah.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:29.099
So that's the point of this whole slide.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:31.780
We're now able to publish to webpages.

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:37.219
And our education people love their PDF files, but we kind of cold turkeyed them.

00:11:37.219 --> 00:11:42.700
We just said, now, here, the reports are going to be on webpages now, and it worked.

00:11:42.700 --> 00:11:47.460
One of the other benefits to us is that we can control access to our reports now.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:52.460
We used to just send out a PDF file, and there it goes, right?

00:11:52.460 --> 00:11:57.179
Every now and then, we go to a meeting, and people are clutching printed versions, but

00:11:57.179 --> 00:12:00.460
now we can update, right?

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:02.020
I'm sure it's happened to you.

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:07.219
You send out a PDF report, and you find some kind of critical error, and then you have

00:12:07.219 --> 00:12:10.940
to republish it and resend it, and now you have a version control problem.

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:17.580
Now Corto and publishing via GitLab solves that problem for us.

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:22.659
In addition, our users get improved functionality, right?

00:12:22.659 --> 00:12:26.659
We have, in our college, I don't even know how many majors, 60-something majors, and

00:12:26.659 --> 00:12:31.580
a lot of our tables are long, because it's by major, by this, by that.

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:35.299
In a PDF, you're pages later.

00:12:35.299 --> 00:12:41.820
Now we can have our users sort by column, and this table doesn't particularly have searchability,

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:43.539
but they can search.

00:12:43.539 --> 00:12:48.700
And so deans might have a different question, for example, from a faculty member in a department.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:53.059
They can sort the table or search the table for the particular piece of information they're

00:12:53.059 --> 00:12:58.539
looking for without having to rifle through pages of PDF output.

00:12:58.539 --> 00:13:04.859
So despite their reluctance to embrace some non-PDF format, it's been a really good thing

00:13:04.859 --> 00:13:08.979
for us, because we've literally unified our workflow.

00:13:08.979 --> 00:13:14.820
We can all work in the same file, and our users get improved functionality, whether

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:17.059
they wanted it or not.

00:13:17.059 --> 00:13:20.700
And Mike is going to talk about a few other enhancements.

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:21.700
Okay.

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:27.340
So I'm going to talk about accuracy.

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:31.900
And so one thing about me is, six years ago, I was teaching ethics, had never written a

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:33.260
line of R code.

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:35.179
I've written quite a bit since then.

00:13:35.179 --> 00:13:42.219
But no formal development training, I've run Linux at home, but that's about it.

00:13:42.539 --> 00:13:47.739
And so what I want to say here is, you can improve accuracy without being a developer,

00:13:47.739 --> 00:13:48.739
essentially.

00:13:48.739 --> 00:13:53.580
So to do that, I'm going to talk about a little example.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:14:00.619
So let's imagine that Susan and I are each given a task to produce a report that involves,

00:14:00.619 --> 00:14:02.979
in some way, computer science majors.

00:14:02.979 --> 00:14:06.140
And we need to know how many there were in 2019 and 2020, right?

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:07.539
These might be separate reports.

00:14:07.539 --> 00:14:11.140
Sometimes we do reports apart from each other, don't talk to each other.

00:14:11.140 --> 00:14:15.979
And what happens, God forbid, we come up with different numbers.

00:14:15.979 --> 00:14:16.979
Oh, no.

00:14:16.979 --> 00:14:17.979
This is embarrassing.

00:14:17.979 --> 00:14:18.979
It's bad.

00:14:18.979 --> 00:14:21.780
So Susan comes up with 2,266.

00:14:21.780 --> 00:14:24.659
I come up with 2,389, right?

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:27.820
This could affect funding for these departments.

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:33.299
It could affect the analysis, right, because there's different students, it seems, in these.

00:14:33.299 --> 00:14:35.659
And it is, again, really embarrassing.

00:14:35.659 --> 00:14:40.580
So I'm going to go through this little example just to show you how you might solve some

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:45.340
of these problems of accuracy.

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:46.500
So why is this happening?

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:47.500
OK.

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:54.340
So the reason in this case is because the term or semester data is coded in our system,

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:55.340
right?

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:57.219
I'm sure you have lots of codes in your work.

00:14:57.219 --> 00:15:00.700
In this case, it's a four-digit code.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:05.140
So for instance, 1204 is spring 2020.

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:06.140
What a great code.

00:15:06.140 --> 00:15:07.419
So this is how it works.

00:15:07.419 --> 00:15:10.820
So the century is the first one.

00:15:10.820 --> 00:15:14.979
So 0 is the 20th century, 1 is the 21st century.

00:15:14.979 --> 00:15:20.380
The second two digits are the last two digits of the year.

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:22.820
But this is not the academic year or the calendar year.

00:15:22.820 --> 00:15:25.739
And this is actually going to come up as an issue, right?

00:15:25.739 --> 00:15:27.260
So I'm not sure what this is.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:29.059
It's a year.

00:15:29.059 --> 00:15:32.859
And then the last digit is fall, spring, summer, right?

00:15:32.859 --> 00:15:37.260
2, 4, and 6, which, you know, I think they were thinking, what if there's a winter

00:15:37.299 --> 00:15:38.299
term someday?

00:15:38.299 --> 00:15:39.299
We want to have room for it.

00:15:39.299 --> 00:15:40.299
So there you go.

00:15:40.299 --> 00:15:41.299
2, 4, 6.

00:15:41.299 --> 00:15:43.140
I love codes.

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:44.140
OK.

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:45.140
So what's happening here?

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:49.739
So this is ambiguity in academic year is the reason why we came up with different numbers.

00:15:49.739 --> 00:15:54.380
So an academic year, and this is a federal, I think it's federal, it's a federal definition.

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:58.260
It's certainly for our reporting, runs from summer to spring.

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:08.219
So the 2019-2020 academic year is from summer of 2019 to spring 2020, right?

00:16:08.219 --> 00:16:11.500
I see I'm the wrong one, of course.

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:14.179
I was thinking the codes were going to help me.

00:16:14.179 --> 00:16:16.559
The codes are never helpful, right?

00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:20.859
So I was looking, oh, look, there's 20, 2020.

00:16:20.859 --> 00:16:23.919
That's the 2019-2020 academic year.

00:16:23.919 --> 00:16:25.479
It's not, of course.

00:16:25.479 --> 00:16:30.159
And so I was unaware of the correct way to find academic year.

00:16:30.159 --> 00:16:34.640
And so that's why I came up with the incorrect answer.

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:35.760
So how do we fix this?

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:37.039
Of course, packages.

00:16:37.039 --> 00:16:38.039
OK.

00:16:38.039 --> 00:16:41.080
So for you, that's obvious, yeah.

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:43.239
I don't need to talk too much about packages.

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:47.919
But my point here is that I believe anyone can write them.

00:16:47.919 --> 00:16:52.719
So I believe, this is just a belief I have, that if you can write a function, and yes,

00:16:52.719 --> 00:16:55.919
you can write a function, I think anyone who can write our code can write a function,

00:16:55.919 --> 00:16:58.200
then you can write a package.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:03.760
And furthermore, you can share them via GitHub or GitLab, and that allows for easy installation

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:05.099
and updates.

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:11.400
So if I update a package, now Susan or Will can download that new version, and all of

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:14.880
our reports change automatically with a fix.

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.079
There are sometimes fixes.

00:17:17.079 --> 00:17:20.280
So we have one package that's called amutils.

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:24.119
It has a function called ACADYear.

00:17:24.119 --> 00:17:28.880
And if you just type it in, you get transparently the code that goes into it.

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:31.680
This is ugly R code, but you can just see it.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:32.819
It's there.

00:17:32.819 --> 00:17:33.819
It's great for learning.

00:17:33.819 --> 00:17:37.839
So if we have a new analyst, they can now see how this process is done.

00:17:37.839 --> 00:17:40.439
You can get documentation for this.

00:17:40.439 --> 00:17:42.800
And this is the ugly stuff you have in RStudio.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:43.800
I think it's beautiful.

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:48.319
But you can also produce beautiful websites with documentation and organize them.

00:17:48.359 --> 00:17:52.719
You get indices that show you all the functions that are involved in here.

00:17:52.719 --> 00:17:55.239
And so ACADemicYear is a really simple function.

00:17:55.239 --> 00:17:57.680
It just converts a term to ACADemicYear.

00:17:57.680 --> 00:18:02.300
We have some complex functions that actually took a long time to figure out and are difficult

00:18:02.300 --> 00:18:05.640
when doing onboarding with new people, and so this allows us to do that.

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:10.599
So finally, you can have different types of packages.

00:18:10.599 --> 00:18:12.880
So we have two types.

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:13.959
So one is public.

00:18:13.959 --> 00:18:20.640
So the AIM utils has innocuous stuff like ACADYear, things that don't sort of expose

00:18:20.640 --> 00:18:24.760
any data or anything or any sort of proprietary information.

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:30.079
We also have an AIM queries package that has queries in them that allow you to access our

00:18:30.079 --> 00:18:37.180
campus databases, and that requires you to sort of credential a bit behind in GitLab.

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:40.359
So we're able to separate those into two different packages.

00:18:40.359 --> 00:18:41.359
Okay.

00:18:41.359 --> 00:18:45.079
So we want you to make your motley career a success.

00:18:45.079 --> 00:18:46.079
